# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: semiconductor-physics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:semiconductor-physics/band-gap] In solid-state physics and solid-state chemistry, a **band gap**, also called a **bandgap** or **energy gap**, is an energy range in a solid where no electronic states exist.
[src:semiconductor-physics/band-gap] In graphs of the electronic band structure of solids, the band gap refers to the energy difference (often expressed in electronvolts) between the top of the valence band and the bottom of the conduction band in insulators and semiconductors.
[src:semiconductor-physics/band-gap] It is the energy required to promote an electron from the valence band to the conduction band.
[src:semiconductor-physics/band-gap] The resulting conduction-band electron (and the electron hole in the valence band) are free to move within the crystal lattice and serve as charge carriers to conduct electric current.
[src:semiconductor-physics/band-gap] It is closely related to the HOMO–LUMO gap in chemistry.
[src:semiconductor-physics/band-gap] If the valence band is completely full and the conduction band is completely empty, then electrons cannot move within the solid because there are no available states.
[src:semiconductor-physics/band-gap] If the electrons are not free to move within the crystal lattice, then there is no generated current due to no net charge carrier mobility.
[src:semiconductor-physics/band-gap] However, if some electrons transfer from the valence band (mostly full) to the conduction band (mostly empty), then current *can* flow (see carrier generation and recombination).
[src:semiconductor-physics/band-gap] Therefore, the band gap is a major factor determining the electrical conductivity of a solid.
[src:semiconductor-physics/band-gap] It is possible to produce laser induced insulator-metal transitions which have already been experimentally observed in some condensed matter systems, like thin films of C60, doped manganites, or in vanadium sesquioxide V2O3.
[src:semiconductor-physics/band-gap] These are special cases of the more general metal-to-nonmetal transitions phenomena which were intensively studied in the last decades.
[src:semiconductor-physics/band-gap] A one-dimensional analytic model of laser induced distortion of band structure was presented for a spatially periodic (cosine) potential.
[src:semiconductor-physics/band-gap] This problem is periodic both in space and time and can be solved analytically using the Kramers-Henneberger co-moving frame.
[src:semiconductor-physics/band-gap] The solutions can be given with the help of the Mathieu functions.
[src:semiconductor-physics/band-gap] Every solid has its own characteristic energy-band structure.
[src:semiconductor-physics/band-gap] This variation in band structure is responsible for the wide range of electrical characteristics observed in various materials.
[src:semiconductor-physics/band-gap] Depending on the dimension, the band structure and spectroscopy can vary.
[src:semiconductor-physics/band-gap] The different types of dimensions are as listed: one dimension, two dimensions, and three dimensions.
[src:semiconductor-physics/band-gap] In semiconductors and insulators, electrons are confined to a number of bands of energy, and forbidden from other regions because there are no allowable electronic states for them to occupy.
[src:semiconductor-physics/band-gap] The term "band gap" refers to the energy difference between the top of the valence band and the bottom of the conduction band.
[src:semiconductor-physics/band-gap] Electrons are able to jump from one band to another.
[src:semiconductor-physics/band-gap] However, in order for a valence band electron to be promoted to the conduction band, it requires a specific minimum amount of energy for the transition.
[src:semiconductor-physics/band-gap] This required energy is an intrinsic characteristic of the solid material.
[src:semiconductor-physics/band-gap] Electrons can gain enough energy to jump to the conduction band by absorbing either a phonon (heat) or a photon (light).
[src:semiconductor-physics/band-gap] A semiconductor is a material with an intermediate-sized, non-zero band gap that behaves as an insulator at T=0K, but allows thermal excitation of electrons into its conduction band at temperatures that are below its melting point.
[src:semiconductor-physics/band-gap] In contrast, a material with a large band gap is an insulator.
[src:semiconductor-physics/band-gap] In conductors, the valence and conduction bands may overlap, so there is no longer a bandgap with forbidden regions of electronic states.
[src:semiconductor-physics/band-gap] The conductivity of intrinsic semiconductors is strongly dependent on the band gap.
[src:semiconductor-physics/band-gap] The only available charge carriers for conduction are the electrons that have enough thermal energy to be excited across the band gap and the electron holes that are left off when such an excitation occurs.
[src:semiconductor-physics/band-gap] Band-gap engineering is the process of controlling or altering the band gap of a material by controlling the composition of certain semiconductor alloys, such as GaAlAs, InGaAs, and InAlAs.
[src:semiconductor-physics/band-gap] It is also possible to construct layered materials with alternating compositions by techniques like molecular-beam epitaxy.
[src:semiconductor-physics/band-gap] These methods are exploited in the design of heterojunction bipolar transistors (HBTs), laser diodes and solar cells.
[src:semiconductor-physics/band-gap] The distinction between semiconductors and insulators is a matter of convention.
[src:semiconductor-physics/band-gap] One approach is to think of semiconductors as a type of insulator with a narrow band gap.
[src:semiconductor-physics/band-gap] Insulators with a larger band gap, usually greater than 4 eV, are not considered semiconductors and generally do not exhibit semiconductive behaviour under practical conditions.
[src:semiconductor-physics/band-gap] Electron mobility also plays a role in determining a material's informal classification.
[src:semiconductor-physics/band-gap] The band-gap energy of semiconductors tends to decrease with increasing temperature.
[src:semiconductor-physics/band-gap] When temperature increases, the amplitude of atomic vibrations increase, leading to larger interatomic spacing.
[src:semiconductor-physics/band-gap] The interaction between the lattice phonons and the free electrons and holes will also affect the band gap to a smaller extent.
[src:semiconductor-physics/band-gap] The relationship between band gap energy and temperature can be described by Varshni's empirical expression (named after Y.
[src:semiconductor-physics/band-gap] Furthermore, lattice vibrations increase with temperature, which increases the effect of electron scattering.
[src:semiconductor-physics/band-gap] Additionally, the number of charge carriers within a semiconductor will increase, as more carriers have the energy required to cross the band-gap threshold and so conductivity of semiconductors also increases with increasing temperature.
[src:semiconductor-physics/band-gap] The external pressure also influences the electronic structure of semiconductors and, therefore, their optical band gaps.
[src:semiconductor-physics/band-gap] In a regular semiconductor crystal, the band gap is fixed owing to continuous energy states.
[src:semiconductor-physics/band-gap] In a quantum dot crystal, energy states are discretized due to the quantum confinement effect.
[src:semiconductor-physics/band-gap] Energy states in the conduction band are pushed upwards in energy, while those in the valence band are pushed downwards, causing the effective band gap to grow with decreasing dot size.
[src:semiconductor-physics/band-gap] Band gaps can be either direct or indirect, depending on the electronic band structure of the material.
[src:semiconductor-physics/band-gap] It was mentioned earlier that the dimensions have different band structure and spectroscopy.
[src:semiconductor-physics/band-gap] For non-metallic solids, which are one dimensional, have optical properties that are dependent on the electronic transitions between valence and conduction bands.
[src:semiconductor-physics/band-gap] In addition, the spectroscopic transition probability is between the initial and final orbital and it depends on the integral. φi is the initial orbital, φf is the final orbital, ʃ φf*ûεφi is the integral, ε is the electric vector, and u is the dipole moment.
[src:semiconductor-physics/band-gap] Two-dimensional structures of solids behave because of the overlap of atomic orbitals.
[src:semiconductor-physics/band-gap] The simplest two-dimensional crystal contains identical atoms arranged on a square lattice.
[src:semiconductor-physics/band-gap] Energy splitting occurs at the Brillouin zone edge for one-dimensional situations because of a weak periodic potential, which produces a gap between bands.
[src:semiconductor-physics/band-gap] The behavior of the one-dimensional situations does not occur for two-dimensional cases because there are extra freedoms of motion.
[src:semiconductor-physics/band-gap] Furthermore, a bandgap can be produced with strong periodic potential for two-dimensional and three-dimensional cases.
[src:semiconductor-physics/band-gap] Based on their band structure, materials are characterised with a direct band gap or indirect band gap.
[src:semiconductor-physics/band-gap] In the free-electron model, k is the momentum of a free electron and assumes unique values within the Brillouin zone that outlines the periodicity of the crystal lattice.
[src:semiconductor-physics/band-gap] If the momentum of the lowest energy state in the conduction band and the highest energy state of the valence band of a material have the same value, then the material has a direct bandgap.
[src:semiconductor-physics/band-gap] If they are not the same, then the material has an indirect band gap and the electronic transition must undergo momentum transfer to satisfy conservation.
[src:semiconductor-physics/band-gap] Such indirect "forbidden" transitions still occur, however at very low probabilities and weaker energy.
[src:semiconductor-physics/band-gap] For materials with a direct band gap, valence electrons can be directly excited into the conduction band by a photon whose energy is larger than the bandgap.
[src:semiconductor-physics/band-gap] In contrast, for materials with an indirect band gap, a photon and phonon must both be involved in a transition from the valence band top to the conduction band bottom, involving a momentum change.
[src:semiconductor-physics/band-gap] LEDs and laser diodes usually emit photons with energy close to and slightly larger than the band gap of the semiconductor material from which they are made.
[src:semiconductor-physics/band-gap] Therefore, as the band gap energy increases, the LED or laser color changes from infrared to red, through the rainbow to violet, then to UV.
[src:semiconductor-physics/band-gap] The optical band gap determines what portion of the solar spectrum a photovoltaic cell absorbs.
[src:semiconductor-physics/band-gap] Strictly, a semiconductor will not absorb photons of energy less than the band gap; whereas most of the photons with energies exceeding the band gap will generate heat.
[src:semiconductor-physics/band-gap] Neither of them contribute to the efficiency of a solar cell.
[src:semiconductor-physics/band-gap] Below are band gap values for some selected materials.
[src:semiconductor-physics/band-gap] For a comprehensive list of band gaps in semiconductors, see List of semiconductor materials.
[src:semiconductor-physics/band-gap] It is possible for an absorbed photon to have just enough energy to generate a bound electron–hole pair (an exciton), but not enough additional energy to separate the two against their mutual electrical attraction.
[src:semiconductor-physics/band-gap] The former energy is called the "optical band gap", while the energy to create an unbound pair so that a macroscopic electrical current will flow is the "electronic band gap" or "transport gap", and is greater than the former by the exciton binding energy.
[src:semiconductor-physics/band-gap] In almost all inorganic semiconductors (silicon, gallium arsenide, etc.) there is very little interaction between electrons and holes, thus the exciton binding energy is very low, and the difference between the two gaps is usually ignored.
[src:semiconductor-physics/band-gap] However, in some systems, including organic semiconductors and single-walled carbon nanotubes, the distinction may be significant.
[src:semiconductor-physics/band-gap] In photonics, band gaps or stop bands are ranges of photon frequencies where, if tunneling effects are neglected, no photons can be transmitted through a material.
[src:semiconductor-physics/band-gap] A material exhibiting this behaviour is known as a photonic crystal.
[src:semiconductor-physics/band-gap] The concept of hyperuniformity has broadened the range of photonic band gap materials, beyond photonic crystals.
[src:semiconductor-physics/band-gap] By applying the technique in supersymmetric quantum mechanics, a new class of optical disordered materials has been suggested, which support band gaps perfectly equivalent to those of crystals or quasicrystals.
[src:semiconductor-physics/band-gap] Similar physics applies to phonons in a phononic crystal.
[src:semiconductor-physics/charge-carrier] In solid state physics, a **charge carrier** is a particle or quasiparticle that is free to move, carrying an electric charge, especially the particles that carry electric charges in electrical conductors.
[src:semiconductor-physics/charge-carrier] In a conducting medium, an electric field can exert force on these free particles, causing a net motion of the particles through the medium; this is what constitutes an electric current.
[src:semiconductor-physics/charge-carrier] The electron and the proton are the **elementary charge carriers**, each carrying one elementary charge (*e*), of the same magnitude and opposite sign.
[src:semiconductor-physics/charge-carrier] In conducting mediums, particles serve to carry charge.
[src:semiconductor-physics/charge-carrier] In many metals, the charge carriers are electrons.
[src:semiconductor-physics/charge-carrier] One or two of the valence electrons from each atom are able to move about freely within the crystal structure of the metal.
[src:semiconductor-physics/charge-carrier] The free electrons are referred to as conduction electrons, and the cloud of free electrons is called a Fermi gas.
[src:semiconductor-physics/charge-carrier] Many metals have electron and hole bands.
[src:semiconductor-physics/charge-carrier] In some, the majority carriers are holes.
[src:semiconductor-physics/charge-carrier] In electrolytes, such as salt water, the charge carriers are ions, which are atoms or molecules that have gained or lost electrons so they are electrically charged.
[src:semiconductor-physics/charge-carrier] Atoms that have gained electrons so they are negatively charged are called anions, atoms that have lost electrons so they are positively charged are called cations.
[src:semiconductor-physics/charge-carrier] Cations and anions of the dissociated liquid also serve as charge carriers in melted ionic solids (see e.g. the Hall–Héroult process for an example of electrolysis of a melted ionic solid).
[src:semiconductor-physics/charge-carrier] Proton conductors are electrolytic conductors employing positive hydrogen ions as carriers.
[src:semiconductor-physics/charge-carrier] In a plasma, an electrically charged gas which is found in electric arcs through air, neon signs, and the sun and stars, the electrons and cations of ionized gas act as charge carriers.
[src:semiconductor-physics/charge-carrier] In a vacuum, free electrons can act as charge carriers.
[src:semiconductor-physics/charge-carrier] In the electronic component known as the vacuum tube (also called *valve*), the mobile electron cloud is generated by a heated metal cathode, by a process called thermionic emission.
[src:semiconductor-physics/charge-carrier] When an electric field is applied strongly enough to draw the electrons into a beam, this may be referred to as a cathode ray, and is the basis of the cathode-ray tube display widely used in televisions and computer monitors until the 2000s.
[src:semiconductor-physics/charge-carrier] In semiconductors, which are the materials used to make electronic components like transistors and integrated circuits, two types of charge carrier are possible.
[src:semiconductor-physics/charge-carrier] In p-type semiconductors, "effective particles" known as electron holes with positive charge move through the crystal lattice, producing an electric current.
[src:semiconductor-physics/charge-carrier] The "holes" are, in effect, electron vacancies in the valence-band electron population of the semiconductor and are treated as charge carriers because they are mobile, moving from atom site to atom site.
[src:semiconductor-physics/charge-carrier] In n-type semiconductors, electrons in the conduction band move through the crystal, resulting in an electric current.
[src:semiconductor-physics/charge-carrier] In some conductors, such as ionic solutions and plasmas, positive and negative charge carriers coexist, so in these cases an electric current consists of the two types of carrier moving in opposite directions.
[src:semiconductor-physics/charge-carrier] In other conductors, such as metals, there are only charge carriers of one polarity, so an electric current in them simply consists of charge carriers moving in one direction.
[src:semiconductor-physics/charge-carrier] There are two recognized types of charge carriers in semiconductors.
[src:semiconductor-physics/charge-carrier] One is electrons, which carry a negative electric charge.
[src:semiconductor-physics/charge-carrier] In addition, it is convenient to treat the traveling vacancies in the valence band electron population (holes) as a second type of charge carrier, which carry a positive charge equal in magnitude to that of an electron.
[src:semiconductor-physics/charge-carrier] When an electron meets with a hole, they recombine and these free carriers effectively vanish.
[src:semiconductor-physics/charge-carrier] The energy released can be either thermal, heating up the semiconductor (*thermal recombination*, one of the sources of waste heat in semiconductors), or released as photons (*optical recombination*, used in LEDs and semiconductor lasers).
[src:semiconductor-physics/charge-carrier] The recombination means an electron which has been excited from the valence band to the conduction band falls back to the empty state in the valence band, known as the holes.
[src:semiconductor-physics/charge-carrier] The holes are the empty states created in the valence band when an electron gets excited after getting some energy to pass the energy gap.
[src:semiconductor-physics/charge-carrier] The more abundant charge carriers are called **majority carriers**, which are primarily responsible for current transport in a piece of semiconductor.
[src:semiconductor-physics/charge-carrier] In n-type semiconductors they are electrons, while in p-type semiconductors they are holes.
[src:semiconductor-physics/charge-carrier] The less abundant charge carriers are called **minority carriers**; in n-type semiconductors they are holes, while in p-type semiconductors they are electrons.
[src:semiconductor-physics/charge-carrier] The concentration of holes and electrons in a doped semiconductor is governed by the mass action law.
[src:semiconductor-physics/charge-carrier] In an intrinsic semiconductor, which does not contain any impurity, the concentrations of both types of carriers are ideally equal.
[src:semiconductor-physics/charge-carrier] If an intrinsic semiconductor is doped with a donor impurity then the majority carriers are electrons.
[src:semiconductor-physics/charge-carrier] If the semiconductor is doped with an acceptor impurity then the majority carriers are holes.
[src:semiconductor-physics/charge-carrier] Minority carriers play an important role in bipolar transistors and solar cells.
[src:semiconductor-physics/charge-carrier] Their role in field-effect transistors (FETs) is a bit more complex: for example, a MOSFET has p-type and n-type regions.
[src:semiconductor-physics/charge-carrier] The transistor action involves the majority carriers of the source and drain regions, but these carriers traverse the body of the opposite type, where they are minority carriers.
[src:semiconductor-physics/charge-carrier] Superconductors have zero electrical resistance and are therefore able to carry current indefinitely.
[src:semiconductor-physics/charge-carrier] This type of conduction is possible by the formation of Cooper pairs.
[src:semiconductor-physics/charge-carrier] At present, superconductors can only be achieved at very low temperatures, for instance by using cryogenic chilling.
[src:semiconductor-physics/charge-carrier] As yet, achieving superconductivity at room temperature remains challenging; it is still a field of ongoing research and experimentation.
[src:semiconductor-physics/charge-carrier] Creating a superconductor that functions at ambient temperature would constitute an important technological break-through, which could potentially contribute to much higher energy efficiency in grid distribution of electricity.
[src:semiconductor-physics/charge-carrier] Under exceptional circumstances, positrons, muons, anti-muons, taus and anti-taus may potentially also carry electric charge.
[src:semiconductor-physics/charge-carrier] This is theoretically possible, yet the very short life-time of these charged particles would render such a current very challenging to maintain at the current state of technology.
[src:semiconductor-physics/charge-carrier] It might be possible to artificially create this type of current, or it might occur in nature during very short lapses of time.
[src:semiconductor-physics/charge-carrier] Electric charge can cause the formation of electromagnetic fields in plasmas, which can lead to the formation of currents or even multiple currents.
[src:semiconductor-physics/charge-carrier] This phenomenon is used in nuclear fusion reactors.
[src:semiconductor-physics/charge-carrier] It also occurs naturally in the cosmos, in the form of jets, nebula winds or cosmic filaments that carry charged particles.
[src:semiconductor-physics/charge-carrier] This cosmic phenomenon is called Birkeland current.
[src:semiconductor-physics/charge-carrier] Considered in general, the electric conductivity of plasmas is a subject of plasma physics.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] In semiconductor production, **doping** is the intentional introduction of impurities into an intrinsic (undoped) semiconductor for the purpose of modulating its electrical, optical and structural properties.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] The doped material is referred to as an extrinsic semiconductor.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] Small numbers of dopant atoms can change the ability of a semiconductor to conduct electricity.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] When on the order of one dopant atom is added per 100 million intrinsic atoms, the doping is said to be *low* or *light*.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] When many more dopant atoms are added, on the order of one per ten thousand atoms, the doping is referred to as *high* or *heavy*.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] This is often shown as *n+* for n-type doping or *p+* for p-type doping.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] (*See the article on semiconductors for a more detailed description of the doping mechanism.*) A semiconductor doped to such high levels that it acts more like a conductor than a semiconductor is referred to as a degenerate semiconductor.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] A semiconductor can be considered i-type semiconductor if it has been doped in equal quantities of p and n.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] In the context of phosphors and scintillators, doping is better known as activation; this is not to be confused with dopant activation in semiconductors.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] Doping is also used to control the color in some pigments.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] The effects of impurities in semiconductors (doping) were long known empirically in such devices as crystal radio detectors and selenium rectifiers.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] For instance, in 1885 Shelford Bidwell, and in 1930 the German scientist Bernhard Gudden, each independently reported that the properties of semiconductors were due to the impurities they contained.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] A doping process was formally developed by John Robert Woodyard working at Sperry Gyroscope Company during World War II.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] Though the word *doping* is not used in it, his US Patent issued in 1950 describes methods for adding tiny amounts of solid elements from the nitrogen column of the periodic table to germanium to produce rectifying devices.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] The demands of his work on radar prevented Woodyard from pursuing further research on semiconductor doping.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] Similar work was performed at Bell Labs by Gordon K.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] Teal and Morgan Sparks, with a US Patent issued in 1953.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] Woodyard's prior patent proved to be the grounds of extensive litigation by Sperry Rand.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] The concentration of the dopant used affects many electrical properties of the semi-conductor.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] Most important is the material's charge carrier concentration.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] In an intrinsic semiconductor under thermal equilibrium, the concentrations of electrons and holes are equivalent.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] where *n*0 is the concentration of conducting electrons, *p*0 is the conducting hole concentration, and *ni* is the material's intrinsic carrier concentration.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] The intrinsic carrier concentration varies between materials and is dependent on temperature.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] Silicon's *ni*, for example, is roughly 1.08×1010 cm−3 at 300 kelvins, about room temperature.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] In general, increased doping leads to increased conductivity due to the higher concentration of carriers.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] Degenerate (very highly doped) semiconductors have conductivity levels comparable to metals and are often used in integrated circuits as a replacement for metal.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] Often superscript plus and minus symbols are used to denote relative doping concentration in semiconductors.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] For example, *n*+ denotes an n-type semiconductor with a high, often degenerate, doping concentration.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] Similarly, *p*− would indicate a very lightly doped p-type material.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] Even degenerate levels of doping imply low concentrations of impurities with respect to the base semiconductor.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] In intrinsic crystalline silicon, there are approximately 5×1022 atoms/cm3.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] Doping concentration for silicon semiconductors may range anywhere from 1013 cm−3 to 1018 cm−3.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] Doping concentration above about 1018 cm−3 is considered degenerate at room temperature.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] Degenerately doped silicon contains a proportion of impurity to silicon on the order of parts per thousand.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] This proportion may be reduced to parts per billion in very lightly doped silicon.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] Typical concentration values fall somewhere in this range and are tailored to produce the desired properties in the device that the semiconductor is intended for.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] Doping a semiconductor in a good crystal introduces allowed energy states within the band gap, but very close to the energy band that corresponds to the dopant type.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] In other words, electron donor impurities create states near the conduction band while electron acceptor impurities create states near the valence band.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] The gap between these energy states and the nearest energy band is usually referred to as dopant-site bonding energy or *EB* and is relatively small.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] For example, the *EB* for boron in silicon bulk is 0.045 eV, compared with silicon's band gap of about 1.12 eV.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] Because *EB* is so small, room temperature is hot enough to thermally ionize practically all of the dopant atoms and create free charge carriers in the conduction or valence bands.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] Dopants also have the important effect of shifting the energy bands relative to the Fermi level.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] The energy band that corresponds with the dopant with the greatest concentration ends up closer to the Fermi level.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] Since the Fermi level must remain constant in a system in thermodynamic equilibrium, stacking layers of materials with different properties leads to many useful electrical properties induced by band bending, if the interfaces can be made cleanly enough.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] For example, the p-n junction's properties are due to the band bending that happens as a result of the necessity to line up the bands in contacting regions of p-type and n-type material.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] The band diagram typically indicates the variation in the valence band and conduction band edges versus some spatial dimension, often denoted *x*.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] The Fermi level is also usually indicated in the diagram.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] Sometimes the *intrinsic Fermi level*, *Ei*, which is the Fermi level in the absence of doping, is shown.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] These diagrams are useful in explaining the operation of many kinds of semiconductor devices.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] For low levels of doping, the relevant energy states are populated sparsely by electrons (conduction band) or holes (valence band).
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] where *E*F is the Fermi level, *E*C is the minimum energy of the conduction band, and *E*V is the maximum energy of the valence band.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] an expression which is independent of the doping level, since *E*C – *E*V (the band gap) does not change with doping.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] where *m**e** and *m**h** are the density of states effective masses of electrons and holes, respectively, quantities that are roughly constant over temperature.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] Some dopants are added as the (usually silicon) boule is grown by Czochralski method, giving each wafer an almost uniform initial doping.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] Alternately, synthesis of semiconductor devices may involve the use of vapor-phase epitaxy.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] In vapor-phase epitaxy, a gas containing the dopant precursor can be introduced into the reactor.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] For example, in the case of n-type gas doping of gallium arsenide, hydrogen sulfide is added, and sulfur is incorporated into the structure.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] This process is characterized by a constant concentration of sulfur on the surface.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] In the case of semiconductors in general, only a very thin layer of the wafer needs to be doped in order to obtain the desired electronic properties.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] Thermal diffusion doping, simply known as diffusion, is widely used in silicon photovoltaics and uses chemicals such as Boron tribromide or diborane as a source for doping with boron.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] This creates a layer of the dopant on the surface of the wafer and this step is called pre-deposition.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] Then a second step, called drive-in, is performed in which the wafer is heated at a higher temperature of 1300 °C to introduce the dopant into the structure of the wafer.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] Diffusion can use solid, liquid or gaseous sources with dopant atoms, such as solid boron nitride for boron, arsenic trioxide for arsenic, liquid arsenic trichloride, gaaseous arsine or phosphine.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] If using a gaseous source, it is carried to the furnace using a carrier gas such as nitrogen, and then allowed to decompose on the hot surface of the wafer, depositing the desired dopant, such as arsenic for example.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] If a liquid source is used, its vapors are carried to the furnace using nitrogen.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] The furnace can be either horizontal or vertical.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] Spin-on glass or spin-on dopant doping is a two-step process.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] First, a mixture of SiO2 and dopants (in a solvent) is applied to a wafer surface by spin-coating.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] Then it is stripping and baked at a certain temperature in a furnace with constant nitrogen+oxygen flow.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] Neutron transmutation doping (NTD) is an unusual doping method for special applications.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] Most commonly, it is used to dope silicon n-type in high-power electronics and semiconductor detectors.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] As neutrons continue to pass through the silicon, more and more phosphorus atoms are produced by transmutation, and therefore the doping becomes more and more strongly n-type.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] NTD is a far less common doping method than diffusion or ion implantation, but it has the advantage of creating an extremely uniform dopant distribution.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] (Note: When discussing periodic table groups, semiconductor physicists always use an older notation, not the current IUPAC group notation.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] For the Group IV semiconductors such as diamond, silicon, germanium, silicon carbide, and silicon–germanium, the most common dopants are acceptors from Group III or donors from Group V elements.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] Boron, arsenic, phosphorus, and occasionally gallium are used to dope silicon.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] Boron is the p-type dopant of choice for silicon integrated circuit production because it diffuses at a rate that makes junction depths easily controllable.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] Phosphorus is typically used for bulk-doping of silicon wafers, while arsenic is used to diffuse junctions, because it diffuses more slowly than phosphorus and is thus more controllable.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] By doping pure silicon with Group V elements such as phosphorus, extra valence electrons are added that become unbounded from individual atoms and allow the compound to be an electrically conductive n-type semiconductor.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] Doping with Group III elements, which are missing the fourth valence electron, creates "broken bonds" (holes) in the silicon lattice that are free to move.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] The result is an electrically conductive p-type semiconductor.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] In this context, a Group V element is said to behave as an electron **donor**, and a Group III element as an **acceptor**.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] This is a key concept in the physics of a diode.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] A very heavily doped semiconductor behaves more like a good conductor (metal) and thus exhibits more linear positive thermal coefficient.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] Such effect is used for instance in sensistors.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] Lower dosage of doping is used in other types (NTC or PTC) thermistors.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] In the following list the "(substituting X)" refers to all of the materials preceding said parenthesis.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] In most cases many types of impurities will be present in the resultant doped semiconductor.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] If an equal number of donors and acceptors are present in the semiconductor, the extra core electrons provided by the former will be used to satisfy the broken bonds due to the latter, so that doping produces no free carriers of either type.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] This phenomenon is known as *compensation*, and occurs at the p-n junction in the vast majority of semiconductor devices.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] Partial compensation, where donors outnumber acceptors or vice versa, allows device makers to repeatedly reverse (invert) the type of a certain layer under the surface of a bulk semiconductor by diffusing or implanting successively higher doses of dopants, so-called **counterdoping**.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] Most modern semiconductor devices are made by successive selective counterdoping steps to create the necessary P and N type areas under the surface of bulk silicon.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] This is an alternative to successively growing such layers by epitaxy.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] Although compensation can be used to increase or decrease the number of donors or acceptors, the electron and hole mobility is always decreased by compensation because mobility is affected by the sum of the donor and acceptor ions.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] Conductive polymers can be doped by adding chemical reactants to oxidize, or sometimes reduce, the system so that electrons are pushed into the conducting orbitals within the already potentially conducting system.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] There are two primary methods of doping a conductive polymer, both of which use an oxidation-reduction (i.e., redox) process.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] **Electrochemical doping** involves suspending a polymer-coated, working electrode in an electrolyte solution in which the polymer is insoluble along with separate counter and reference electrodes.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] An electric potential difference is created between the electrodes that causes a charge and the appropriate counter ion from the electrolyte to enter the polymer in the form of electron addition (i.e., n-doping) or removal (i.e., p-doping).
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] N-doping is much less common because the Earth's atmosphere is oxygen-rich, thus creating an oxidizing environment.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] An electron-rich, n-doped polymer will react immediately with elemental oxygen to *de-dope* (i.e., reoxidize to the neutral state) the polymer.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] Thus, chemical n-doping must be performed in an environment of inert gas (e.g., argon).
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] Electrochemical n-doping is far more common in research, because it is easier to exclude oxygen from a solvent in a sealed flask.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] However, it is unlikely that n-doped conductive polymers are available commercially.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] Molecular dopants are preferred in doping molecular semiconductors due to their compatibilities of processing with the host, that is, similar evaporation temperatures or controllable solubility.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] Additionally, the relatively large sizes of molecular dopants compared with those of metal ion dopants (such as Li+ and Mo6+) are generally beneficial, yielding excellent spatial confinement for use in multilayer structures, such as OLEDs and Organic solar cells.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] Typical p-type dopants include F4-TCNQ and Mo(tfd)3.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] However, similar to the problem encountered in doping conductive polymers, air-stable n-dopants suitable for materials with low electron affinity (EA) are still elusive.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] Recently, photoactivation with a combination of cleavable dimeric dopants, such as [RuCp∗Mes]2, suggests a new path to realize effective n-doping in low-EA materials.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] The inclusion of dopant elements to impart dilute magnetism is of growing significance in the field of magnetic semiconductors.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] The presence of disperse ferromagnetic species is key to the functionality of emerging spintronics, a class of systems that utilise electron spin in addition to charge.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] Using density functional theory (DFT) the temperature dependent magnetic behaviour of dopants within a given lattice can be modeled to identify candidate semiconductor systems.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] The sensitive dependence of a semiconductor's properties on dopants has provided an extensive range of tunable phenomena to explore and apply to devices.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] It is possible to identify the effects of a solitary dopant on commercial device performance as well as on the fundamental properties of a semiconductor material.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] New applications have become available that require the discrete character of a single dopant, such as single-spin devices in the area of quantum information or single-dopant transistors.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] Dramatic advances in the past decade towards observing, controllably creating and manipulating single dopants, as well as their application in novel devices have allowed opening the new field of solotronics (solitary dopant optoelectronics).
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] Electrons or holes introduced by doping are mobile, and can be spatially separated from dopant atoms they have dissociated from.
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] Ionized donors and acceptors however attract electrons and holes, respectively, so this spatial separation requires abrupt changes of dopant levels, of band gap (e.g. a quantum well), or built-in electric fields (e.g. in case of noncentrosymmetric crystals).
[src:semiconductor-physics/doping-semiconductor] This technique is called modulation doping and is advantageous owing to suppressed carrier-donor scattering, allowing very high mobility to be attained.
[src:semiconductor-physics/electron-hole] In physics, chemistry, and electronic engineering, an **electron hole** (often simply called a **hole**) is a quasiparticle denoting the lack of an electron at a position where one could exist in an atom or atomic lattice.
[src:semiconductor-physics/electron-hole] Since in a normal atom or crystal lattice the negative charge of the electrons is balanced by the positive charge of the atomic nuclei, the absence of an electron leaves a net positive charge at the hole's location.
[src:semiconductor-physics/electron-hole] Holes in a metal or semiconductor crystal lattice can move through the lattice as electrons can, and act similarly to positively-charged particles.
[src:semiconductor-physics/electron-hole] They play an important role in the operation of semiconductor devices such as transistors, diodes (including light-emitting diodes) and integrated circuits.
[src:semiconductor-physics/electron-hole] If an electron is excited into a higher state it leaves a hole in its old state.
[src:semiconductor-physics/electron-hole] This meaning is used in Auger electron spectroscopy (and other x-ray techniques), in computational chemistry, and to explain the low electron-electron scattering-rate in crystals (metals and semiconductors).
[src:semiconductor-physics/electron-hole] Although they act like elementary particles, holes are rather quasiparticles; they are different from the positron, which is the antiparticle of the electron.
[src:semiconductor-physics/electron-hole] In crystals, electronic band structure calculations show that electrons have a negative effective mass at the top of a band.
[src:semiconductor-physics/electron-hole] Although negative mass is unintuitive, a more familiar and intuitive picture emerges by considering a hole, which has a positive charge and a positive mass, instead.
[src:semiconductor-physics/electron-hole] In semiconductors, an *electron hole* (usually referred to simply as a *hole*) is the absence of an electron from a full valence band.
[src:semiconductor-physics/electron-hole] A hole is essentially a way to conceptualize the interactions of the electrons within a nearly full valence band of a crystal lattice, which is missing a small fraction of its electrons.
[src:semiconductor-physics/electron-hole] In some ways, the behavior of a hole within a semiconductor crystal lattice is comparable to that of the bubble in a full bottle of water.
[src:semiconductor-physics/electron-hole] More generally, a hole is defined as the absence of an electron relative to the system's ground state.
[src:semiconductor-physics/electron-hole] This concept applies not only to semiconductors but also to metals with partially filled bands and other electronic systems.
[src:semiconductor-physics/electron-hole] A hole with wavevector *k* and spin $\uparrow$ is created by removing an electron with a wavevector *$-k$* and spin $\downarrow$ .
[src:semiconductor-physics/electron-hole] The hole concept was pioneered in 1929 by Rudolf Peierls, who analyzed the Hall effect using Bloch's theorem, and demonstrated that a nearly full and a nearly empty Brillouin zones give the opposite Hall voltages.
[src:semiconductor-physics/electron-hole] Imagine a row of people seated in an auditorium, where there are no spare chairs.
[src:semiconductor-physics/electron-hole] Someone in the middle of the row wants to leave, so he jumps over the back of the seat into another row, and walks out.
[src:semiconductor-physics/electron-hole] The empty row is analogous to the conduction band, and the person walking out is analogous to a conduction electron.
[src:semiconductor-physics/electron-hole] Now imagine someone else comes along and wants to sit down.
[src:semiconductor-physics/electron-hole] The empty row has a poor view; so he does not want to sit there.
[src:semiconductor-physics/electron-hole] Instead, a person in the crowded row moves into the empty seat the first person left behind.
[src:semiconductor-physics/electron-hole] The empty seat moves one spot closer to the edge and the person waiting to sit down.
[src:semiconductor-physics/electron-hole] The next person follows, and the next, et cetera.
[src:semiconductor-physics/electron-hole] One could say that the empty seat moves towards the edge of the row.
[src:semiconductor-physics/electron-hole] Once the empty seat reaches the edge, the new person can sit down.
[src:semiconductor-physics/electron-hole] In the process everyone in the row has moved along.
[src:semiconductor-physics/electron-hole] If those people were negatively charged (like electrons), this movement would constitute conduction.
[src:semiconductor-physics/electron-hole] If the seats themselves were positively charged, then only the vacant seat would be positive.
[src:semiconductor-physics/electron-hole] This is a very simple model of how hole conduction works.
[src:semiconductor-physics/electron-hole] Instead of analyzing the movement of an empty state in the valence band as the movement of many separate electrons, a single equivalent imaginary particle called a "hole" is considered.
[src:semiconductor-physics/electron-hole] In an applied electric field, the electrons move in one direction, corresponding to the hole moving in the other.
[src:semiconductor-physics/electron-hole] If a hole associates itself with a neutral atom, that atom loses an electron and becomes positive.
[src:semiconductor-physics/electron-hole] Therefore, the hole is taken to have positive charge of +*e*, precisely the opposite of the electron charge.
[src:semiconductor-physics/electron-hole] In reality, due to the uncertainty principle of quantum mechanics, combined with the energy levels available in the crystal, the hole is not localizable to a single position as described in the previous example.
[src:semiconductor-physics/electron-hole] Rather, the positive charge which represents the hole spans an area in the crystal lattice covering many hundreds of unit cells.
[src:semiconductor-physics/electron-hole] This is equivalent to being unable to tell which broken bond corresponds to the "missing" electron.
[src:semiconductor-physics/electron-hole] Conduction band electrons are similarly delocalized.
[src:semiconductor-physics/electron-hole] The analogy above is quite simplified, and cannot explain why holes in semiconductors create an opposite effect to electrons in the Hall effect and Seebeck effect.
[src:semiconductor-physics/electron-hole] A more precise and detailed explanation follows.
[src:semiconductor-physics/electron-hole] A dispersion relation is the relationship between wavevector (k-vector) and energy in a band, part of the electronic band structure.
[src:semiconductor-physics/electron-hole] In quantum mechanics, the electrons are waves, and energy is the wave frequency.
[src:semiconductor-physics/electron-hole] A localized electron is a wavepacket, and the motion of an electron is given by the formula for the group velocity of a wave.
[src:semiconductor-physics/electron-hole] An electric field affects an electron by gradually shifting all the wavevectors in the wavepacket, and the electron accelerates when its wave group velocity changes.
[src:semiconductor-physics/electron-hole] Therefore, again, the way an electron responds to forces is entirely determined by its dispersion relation.
[src:semiconductor-physics/electron-hole] An electron floating in space has the dispersion relation *E* = ℏ2*k*2/(2*m*), where *m* is the (real) electron mass and ℏ is reduced Planck constant.
[src:semiconductor-physics/electron-hole] Near the bottom of the conduction band of a semiconductor, the dispersion relation is instead *E* = ℏ2*k*2/(2*m**) (*m** is the *effective mass*), so a conduction-band electron responds to forces *as if* it had the mass *m**.
[src:semiconductor-physics/electron-hole] The dispersion relation near the top of the valence band is *E* = ℏ2*k*2/(2*m**) with *negative* effective mass.
[src:semiconductor-physics/electron-hole] So electrons near the top of the valence band behave like they have negative mass.
[src:semiconductor-physics/electron-hole] When a force pulls the electrons to the right, these electrons actually move left.
[src:semiconductor-physics/electron-hole] This is solely due to the shape of the valence band and is unrelated to whether the band is full or empty.
[src:semiconductor-physics/electron-hole] If you could somehow empty out the valence band and just put one electron near the valence band maximum (an unstable situation), this electron would move the "wrong way" in response to forces.
[src:semiconductor-physics/electron-hole] A perfectly full band always has zero current.
[src:semiconductor-physics/electron-hole] One way to think about this fact is that the electron states near the top of the band have negative effective mass, and those near the bottom of that band have positive effective mass, so the net motion is exactly zero.
[src:semiconductor-physics/electron-hole] If an otherwise-almost-full valence band has a state *without* an electron in it, we say that this state is occupied by a hole.
[src:semiconductor-physics/electron-hole] There is a mathematical shortcut for calculating the current due to every electron in the whole valence band: Start with zero current (the total if the band were full), and *subtract* the current due to the electrons that *would* be in each hole state if it wasn't a hole.
[src:semiconductor-physics/electron-hole] This fact follows from the discussion and definition above.
[src:semiconductor-physics/electron-hole] This is an example where the auditorium analogy above is misleading.
[src:semiconductor-physics/electron-hole] When a person moves left in a full auditorium, an empty seat moves right.
[src:semiconductor-physics/electron-hole] But in this section we are imagining how electrons move through k-space, not real space, and the effect of a force is to move all the electrons through k-space in the same direction at the same time.
[src:semiconductor-physics/electron-hole] In this context, a better analogy is a bubble underwater in a river: The bubble moves the same direction as the water, not the opposite.
[src:semiconductor-physics/electron-hole] Since force = mass × acceleration, a negative-effective-mass electron near the top of the valence band would move the opposite direction as a positive-effective-mass electron near the bottom of the conduction band, in response to a given electric or magnetic force.
[src:semiconductor-physics/electron-hole] Therefore, a hole moves this way as well.
[src:semiconductor-physics/electron-hole] From the above, a hole (1) carries a positive charge, and (2) responds to electric and magnetic fields as if it had a positive charge and positive mass.
[src:semiconductor-physics/electron-hole] (The latter is because a particle with positive charge and positive mass respond to electric and magnetic fields in the same way as a particle with a negative charge and negative mass.) That explains why holes can be treated in all situations as ordinary positively charged quasiparticles.
[src:semiconductor-physics/electron-hole] In some semiconductors, such as silicon, the hole's effective mass is dependent on a direction (anisotropic), however a value averaged over all directions can be used for some macroscopic calculations.
[src:semiconductor-physics/electron-hole] In most semiconductors, the effective mass of a hole is much larger than that of an electron.
[src:semiconductor-physics/electron-hole] This results in lower mobility for holes under the influence of an electric field and this may slow down the speed of the electronic device made of that semiconductor.
[src:semiconductor-physics/electron-hole] This is one major reason for adopting electrons as the primary charge carriers, whenever possible in semiconductor devices, rather than holes.
[src:semiconductor-physics/electron-hole] This is also why NMOS logic is faster than PMOS logic.
[src:semiconductor-physics/electron-hole] OLED screens have been modified to reduce imbalance resulting in non radiative recombination by adding extra layers and/or decreasing electron density on one plastic layer so electrons and holes precisely balance within the emission zone.
[src:semiconductor-physics/electron-hole] However, in many semiconductor devices, both electrons *and* holes play an essential role.
[src:semiconductor-physics/electron-hole] Examples include p–n diodes, bipolar transistors, and CMOS logic.
[src:semiconductor-physics/electron-hole] A hole in semiconductor physics, defined as the absence of an electron in a nearly full valence band, has a formal analogy to the positron in Paul Dirac's relativistic theory of the electron (See Dirac equation).
[src:semiconductor-physics/electron-hole] In both cases, the system is described as a filled sea of negative-energy or valence states, and the removal of an electron leads to a positively charged entity that can carry current.
[src:semiconductor-physics/electron-hole] The analogy extends to their electromagnetic behavior: both holes and positrons have a charge that is equal and opposite to that of an electron.
[src:semiconductor-physics/electron-hole] When an electron and positron collide, they annihilate each other and the energy is emitted as photons or other radiation.
[src:semiconductor-physics/electron-hole] An analogous process, recombination, happens in semiconductors, and can be described as an electron falling to the empty hole state and filling it, emitting radiation.
[src:semiconductor-physics/electron-hole] However, there are also limitations to this analogy.
[src:semiconductor-physics/electron-hole] Due to the symmetries of Dirac's theory, positron and electron have exactly the same mass, while holes and electrons in crystals generally have different masses.
[src:semiconductor-physics/electron-hole] The positron is a real particle with positive inertial mass and rest energy, while the hole is a quasiparticle whose inertial mass is negative.
[src:semiconductor-physics/electron-hole] For this reason the responses differ in non-inertial frames: in an accelerating crystal lattice, a positron lags behind, whereas a hole moves forward with the lattice.
[src:semiconductor-physics/electron-hole] These differences also appear in composite systems; for example, excitons (electron–hole pairs) move rigidly with the lattice and carry no net momentum, unlike positronium atoms (electron–positron pairs), which gain momentum and energy relative to an accelerating frame.
[src:semiconductor-physics/electron-hole] The concept of an electron hole in solid-state physics predates the concept of a hole in Dirac equation, but there is no evidence that it would have influenced Dirac's thinking.
[src:semiconductor-physics/p-n-junction] A **p–n junction** is a combination of two types of semiconductor materials, p-type and n-type, in a single crystal.
[src:semiconductor-physics/p-n-junction] The "n" (negative) side contains freely-moving electrons, while the "p" (positive) side contains freely-moving electron holes.
[src:semiconductor-physics/p-n-junction] Connecting the two materials causes creation of a depletion region near the boundary, as the free electrons fill the available holes, which in turn allows electric current to pass through the junction only in one direction.
[src:semiconductor-physics/p-n-junction] p–n junctions represent the simplest case of a semiconductor electronic device; a p–n junction by itself, when connected on both sides to a circuit, is a diode.
[src:semiconductor-physics/p-n-junction] More complex circuit components can be created by further combinations of p-type and n-type semiconductors; for example, the bipolar junction transistor (BJT) is a semiconductor in the form n–p–n or p–n–p.
[src:semiconductor-physics/p-n-junction] Combinations of such semiconductor devices on a single chip allow for the creation of integrated circuits.
[src:semiconductor-physics/p-n-junction] Solar cells and light-emitting diodes (LEDs) are essentially p–n junctions where the semiconductor materials are chosen, and the component's geometry designed, to maximise the desired effect (light absorption or emission).
[src:semiconductor-physics/p-n-junction] A Schottky junction is a similar case to a p–n junction, where instead of an n-type semiconductor, a metal directly serves the role of the "negative" charge provider.
[src:semiconductor-physics/p-n-junction] The invention of the p–n junction is usually attributed to American physicist Russell Ohl of Bell Laboratories in 1939.
[src:semiconductor-physics/p-n-junction] Two years later (1941), Vadim Lashkaryov reported discovery of p–n junctions in Cu2O and silver sulphide photocells and selenium rectifiers.
[src:semiconductor-physics/p-n-junction] The modern theory of p–n junctions was elucidated by William Shockley in his classic work *Electrons and Holes in Semiconductors* (1950).
[src:semiconductor-physics/p-n-junction] A p-doped semiconductor (that is, one where impurities such as Boron are introduced into its crystal lattice) is relatively conductive.
[src:semiconductor-physics/p-n-junction] The same is true of an n-doped semiconductor, but the junction between them—the boundary where the p-doped and n-doped semiconductor materials meet—can become depleted of charge carriers such as electrons, depending on the relative voltages of the two semiconductor regions.
[src:semiconductor-physics/p-n-junction] By manipulating the flow of charge carriers across this depleted layer, p–n junctions can be used as diodes: circuit elements that allow a flow of electricity in one direction but not in the opposite direction.
[src:semiconductor-physics/p-n-junction] This property makes the p–n junction extremely useful in modern semiconductor electronics.
[src:semiconductor-physics/p-n-junction] Negative charge carriers (electrons) can easily flow through the junction from n to p but not from p to n, and the reverse is true for positive charge carriers (Electron hole).
[src:semiconductor-physics/p-n-junction] When the p–n junction is forward-biased, charge carriers flow freely due to the reduction in energy barriers seen by electrons and holes.
[src:semiconductor-physics/p-n-junction] When the p–n junction is reverse-biased, however, the junction barrier (and therefore resistance) becomes greater and charge flow is minimal.
[src:semiconductor-physics/p-n-junction] In a p–n junction, without an external applied voltage, an equilibrium condition is reached in which a potential difference forms across the junction.
[src:semiconductor-physics/p-n-junction] This potential difference is called *built-in potential* $V_{\rm {bi}}$ .
[src:semiconductor-physics/p-n-junction] At the junction, some of the free electrons in the n-type wander into the p-type due to random thermal migration ("diffusion").
[src:semiconductor-physics/p-n-junction] As they diffuse into the p-type they combine with electron holes, and cancel each other out.
[src:semiconductor-physics/p-n-junction] In a similar way, some of the positive holes in the p-type diffuse into the n-type and combine with free electrons and cancel each other out.
[src:semiconductor-physics/p-n-junction] The positively charged ("donor") dopant atoms in the n-type are part of the crystal, and cannot move.
[src:semiconductor-physics/p-n-junction] Thus, in the n-type, a region near the junction has a fixed amount of positive charge.
[src:semiconductor-physics/p-n-junction] The negatively charged ("acceptor") dopant atoms in the p-type are part of the crystal, and cannot move.
[src:semiconductor-physics/p-n-junction] Thus, in the p-type, a region near the junction becomes negatively charged.
[src:semiconductor-physics/p-n-junction] The result is a region near the junction that acts to repel the mobile charges away from the junction because of the electric field that these charged regions create.
[src:semiconductor-physics/p-n-junction] The region near the p–n interface loses electrical neutrality and most of its mobile carriers, forming the depletion layer (see figure A).
[src:semiconductor-physics/p-n-junction] The electric field created in the space charge then tends to counteract further diffusion, resulting in equilibrium.
[src:semiconductor-physics/p-n-junction] The carrier concentration profile at equilibrium is shown in figure A with blue and red lines.
[src:semiconductor-physics/p-n-junction] Also shown are the two counterbalancing phenomena that establish equilibrium.
[src:semiconductor-physics/p-n-junction] The space charge region is a zone with a net charge provided by the fixed ions (donors or acceptors) that have been left *uncovered* by majority carrier diffusion.
[src:semiconductor-physics/p-n-junction] When equilibrium is reached, the charge density is approximated by the displayed step function.
[src:semiconductor-physics/p-n-junction] In fact, since the y-axis of figure A is log-scale, the region is almost completely depleted of majority carriers (leaving a charge density equal to the net doping level), and the edge between the space charge region and the neutral region is quite sharp (see figure B, Q(x) graph).
[src:semiconductor-physics/p-n-junction] The space charge region has the same magnitude of charge on both sides of the p–n interfaces, thus it extends farther on the less doped side in this example (the n side in figures A and B).
[src:semiconductor-physics/p-n-junction] In forward bias, the p-type is connected with a positive electrical terminal and the n-type is connected with a negative terminal.
[src:semiconductor-physics/p-n-junction] The panels show **energy band diagram**, **electric field**, and **net charge density**.
[src:semiconductor-physics/p-n-junction] The built-in potential of the semiconductor varies, depending on the concentration of doping atoms.
[src:semiconductor-physics/p-n-junction] In this example, both p and n junctions are doped at a 1e15 cm−3 (160 μC/cm3) doping level, leading to built-in potential of ~0.59 volts.
[src:semiconductor-physics/p-n-junction] Reducing depletion width can be inferred from the shrinking movement of carriers across the p–n junction, which as a consequence reduces electrical resistance.
[src:semiconductor-physics/p-n-junction] Electrons that cross the p–n junction into the p-type material (or holes that cross into the n-type material) diffuse into the nearby neutral region.
[src:semiconductor-physics/p-n-junction] The amount of minority diffusion in the near-neutral zones determines the amount of current that can flow through the diode.
[src:semiconductor-physics/p-n-junction] Only majority carriers (electrons in n-type material or holes in p-type) can flow through a semiconductor for a macroscopic length.
[src:semiconductor-physics/p-n-junction] With this in mind, consider the flow of electrons across the junction.
[src:semiconductor-physics/p-n-junction] The forward bias causes a force on the electrons pushing them from the N side toward the P side.
[src:semiconductor-physics/p-n-junction] With forward bias, the depletion region is narrow enough that electrons can cross the junction and *inject* into the p-type material.
[src:semiconductor-physics/p-n-junction] However, they do not continue to flow through the p-type material indefinitely, because it is energetically favorable for them to recombine with holes.
[src:semiconductor-physics/p-n-junction] The average length an electron travels through the p-type material before recombining is called the *diffusion length*, and it is typically on the order of micrometers.
[src:semiconductor-physics/p-n-junction] Although the electrons penetrate only a short distance into the p-type material, the electric current continues uninterrupted, because holes (the majority carriers) begin to flow in the opposite direction.
[src:semiconductor-physics/p-n-junction] The total current (the sum of the electron and hole currents) is constant in space, because any variation would cause charge buildup over time (this is Kirchhoff's current law).
[src:semiconductor-physics/p-n-junction] The flow of holes from the p-type region into the n-type region is exactly analogous to the flow of electrons from N to P (electrons and holes swap roles and the signs of all currents and voltages are reversed).
[src:semiconductor-physics/p-n-junction] The electrons and holes travel in opposite directions, but they also have opposite charges, so the overall current is in the same direction on both sides of the diode, as required.
[src:semiconductor-physics/p-n-junction] The Shockley diode equation models the forward-bias operational characteristics of a p–n junction outside the avalanche (reverse-biased conducting) region.
[src:semiconductor-physics/p-n-junction] Connecting the *p-type* region to the *negative* terminal of the voltage supply and the *n-type* region to the *positive* terminal corresponds to reverse bias.
[src:semiconductor-physics/p-n-junction] If a diode is reverse-biased, the voltage at the cathode is comparatively higher than at the anode.
[src:semiconductor-physics/p-n-junction] Therefore, very little current flows until the diode breaks down.
[src:semiconductor-physics/p-n-junction] The connections are illustrated in the adjacent diagram.
[src:semiconductor-physics/p-n-junction] Because the p-type material is now connected to the negative terminal of the power supply, the 'holes' in the p-type material are pulled away from the junction, leaving behind charged ions and causing the width of the depletion region to increase.
[src:semiconductor-physics/p-n-junction] Likewise, because the n-type region is connected to the positive terminal, the electrons are pulled away from the junction, with similar effect.
[src:semiconductor-physics/p-n-junction] This increases the voltage barrier causing a high resistance to the flow of charge carriers, thus allowing minimal electric current to cross the p–n junction.
[src:semiconductor-physics/p-n-junction] The increase in resistance of the p–n junction results in the junction behaving as an insulator.
[src:semiconductor-physics/p-n-junction] The strength of the depletion zone electric field increases as the reverse-bias voltage increases.
[src:semiconductor-physics/p-n-junction] Once the electric field intensity increases beyond a critical level, the p–n junction depletion zone breaks down and current begins to flow, usually by either the Zener or the avalanche breakdown processes.
[src:semiconductor-physics/p-n-junction] Both of these breakdown processes are non-destructive and are reversible, as long as the amount of current flowing does not reach levels that cause the semiconductor material to overheat and cause thermal damage.
[src:semiconductor-physics/p-n-junction] This effect is used to advantage in Zener diode regulator circuits.
[src:semiconductor-physics/p-n-junction] Zener diodes have a low breakdown voltage.
[src:semiconductor-physics/p-n-junction] A standard value for breakdown voltage is for instance 5.6 V.
[src:semiconductor-physics/p-n-junction] This means that the voltage at the cathode cannot be more than about 5.6 V higher than the voltage at the anode (though there is a slight rise with current), because the diode breaks down, and therefore conducts, if the voltage gets any higher.
[src:semiconductor-physics/p-n-junction] This effect limits the voltage over the diode.
[src:semiconductor-physics/p-n-junction] Another application of reverse biasing is Varactor diodes, where the width of the depletion zone (controlled with the reverse bias voltage) changes the capacitance of the diode.
[src:semiconductor-physics/p-n-junction] For a p–n junction, let $C_{A}(x)$ be the concentration of negatively-charged acceptor atoms and $C_{D}(x)$ be the concentrations of positively-charged donor atoms.
[src:semiconductor-physics/p-n-junction] Let $N_{0}(x)$ and $P_{0}(x)$ be the equilibrium concentrations of electrons and holes respectively.
[src:semiconductor-physics/p-n-junction] where V is the electric potential, $\rho$ is the charge density, $\varepsilon$ is permittivity and q is the magnitude of the electron charge.
[src:semiconductor-physics/p-n-junction] Let $d_{p}$ be the width of the depletion region on the p-side and $d_{n}$ the width of the depletion region on the n-side.
[src:semiconductor-physics/p-n-junction] because the total charge on the p and the n side of the depletion region sums to zero.
[src:semiconductor-physics/p-n-junction] $\Delta V$ can be written as $\Delta V_{0}+\Delta V_{\text{ext}}$ , where we have broken up the voltage difference into the equilibrium plus external components.
[src:semiconductor-physics/p-n-junction] The *Shockley ideal diode equation* characterizes the current across a p–n junction as a function of external voltage and ambient conditions (temperature, choice of semiconductor, etc.).
[src:semiconductor-physics/p-n-junction] To see how it can be derived, we must examine the various reasons for current.
[src:semiconductor-physics/p-n-junction] The convention is that the forward (+) direction be pointed against the diode's built-in potential gradient at equilibrium.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] A **semiconductor device** is an electronic component that relies on the electronic properties of a semiconductor material (primarily silicon, germanium, and gallium arsenide, as well as organic semiconductors) for its function.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] Its conductivity lies between conductors and insulators.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] Semiconductor devices have replaced vacuum tubes in most applications.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] They conduct electric current in the solid state, rather than as free electrons across a vacuum (typically liberated by thermionic emission) or as free electrons and ions through an ionized gas.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] Semiconductor devices are manufactured both as single discrete devices and as integrated circuits, which consist of two or more devices—which can number from the hundreds to the billions—manufactured and interconnected on a single semiconductor wafer (also called a substrate).
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] Semiconductor materials are useful because their behavior can be easily manipulated by the deliberate addition of impurities, known as doping.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] Semiconductor conductivity can be controlled by the introduction of an electric or magnetic field, by exposure to light or heat, or by the mechanical deformation of a doped monocrystalline silicon grid; thus, semiconductors can make excellent sensors.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] Current conduction in a semiconductor occurs due to mobile or "free" electrons and electron holes, collectively known as charge carriers.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] Doping a semiconductor with a small proportion of an atomic impurity, such as phosphorus or boron, greatly increases the number of free electrons or holes within the semiconductor.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] When a doped semiconductor contains excess holes, it is called a p-type semiconductor (*p* for positive electric charge); when it contains excess free electrons, it is called an n-type semiconductor (*n* for a negative electric charge).
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] A majority of mobile charge carriers have negative charges.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] The manufacture of semiconductors controls precisely the location and concentration of p- and n-type dopants.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] The connection of n-type and p-type semiconductors form p–n junctions.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] The most common semiconductor device in the world is the MOSFET (metal–oxide–semiconductor field-effect transistor), also called the MOS transistor.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] As of 2013, billions of MOS transistors are manufactured every day.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] Semiconductor devices made per year have been growing by 9.1% on average since 1978, and shipments in 2018 are predicted for the first time to exceed 1 trillion, meaning that well over 7 trillion have been made to date.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] A semiconductor diode is a device typically made from a single p–n junction.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] At the junction of a p-type and an n-type semiconductor, there forms a depletion region where current conduction is inhibited by the lack of mobile charge carriers.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] When the device is *forward biased* (connected with the p-side, having a higher electric potential than the n-side), this depletion region is diminished, allowing for significant conduction.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] Contrariwise, only a very small current can be achieved when the diode is *reverse biased* (connected with the n-side at higher electric potential than the p-side, and thus the depletion region expanded).
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] Exposing a semiconductor to light can generate electron–hole pairs, which increases the number of free carriers and thereby the conductivity.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] Diodes optimized to take advantage of this phenomenon are known as *photodiodes*.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] Compound semiconductor diodes can also produce light, as in light-emitting diodes and laser diodes.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] Bipolar junction transistors (BJTs) are formed from two p–n junctions, in either n–p–n or p–n–p configuration.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] The middle, or *base*, the region between the junctions is typically very narrow.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] The other regions, and their associated terminals, are known as the *emitter* and the *collector*.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] A small current injected through the junction between the base and the emitter changes the properties of the base-collector junction so that it can conduct current even though it is reverse biased.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] This creates a much larger current between the collector and emitter, controlled by the base-emitter current.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] Another type of transistor, the field-effect transistor (FET), operates on the principle that semiconductor conductivity can be increased or decreased by the presence of an electric field.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] An electric field can increase the number of free electrons and holes in a semiconductor, thereby changing its conductivity.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] The field may be applied by a reverse-biased p–n junction, forming a *junction field-effect transistor* (JFET) or by an electrode insulated from the bulk material by an oxide layer, forming a *metal–oxide–semiconductor field-effect transistor* (MOSFET).
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] The metal-oxide-semiconductor FET (MOSFET, or MOS transistor), a solid-state device, is by far the most used widely semiconductor device today.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] It accounts for at least 99.9% of all transistors, and there have been an estimated 13 sextillion MOSFETs manufactured between 1960 and 2018.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] The *gate* electrode is charged to produce an electric field that controls the conductivity of a "channel" between two terminals, called the *source* and *drain*.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] Depending on the type of carrier in the channel, the device may be an *n-channel* (for electrons) or a *p-channel* (for holes) MOSFET.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] Although the MOSFET is named in part for its "metal" gate, in modern devices polysilicon is typically used instead.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] By far, silicon (Si) is the most widely used material in semiconductor devices.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] Its combination of low raw material cost, relatively simple processing, and a useful temperature range makes it currently the best compromise among the various competing materials.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] Silicon used in semiconductor device manufacturing is currently fabricated into boules that are large enough in diameter to allow the production of 300 mm (12 in.) wafers.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] Germanium (Ge) was a widely used early semiconductor material but its thermal sensitivity makes it less useful than silicon.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] Today, germanium is often alloyed with silicon for use in very-high-speed SiGe devices; IBM is a major producer of such devices.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] Gallium Nitride (GaN) is gaining popularity in high-power applications including power ICs, light-emitting diodes (LEDs), and RF components due to its high strength and thermal conductivity.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] Compared to silicon, GaN's band gap is more than 3 times wider at 3.4 eV and it conducts electrons 1,000 times more efficiently.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] Other less common materials are also in use or under investigation.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] IMPATT diodes have also been fabricated from SiC.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] Various indium compounds (indium arsenide, indium antimonide, and indium phosphide) are also being used in LEDs and solid-state laser diodes.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] Selenium sulfide is being studied in the manufacture of photovoltaic solar cells.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] The most common use for organic semiconductors is organic light-emitting diodes.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] All transistor types can be used as the building blocks of logic gates, which are fundamental in the design of digital circuits.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] In digital circuits like microprocessors, transistors act as on-off switches; in the MOSFET, for instance, the voltage applied to the gate determines whether the switch is on or off.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] Transistors used for analog circuits do not act as on-off switches; rather, they respond to a continuous range of inputs with a continuous range of outputs.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] Common analog circuits include amplifiers and oscillators.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] Circuits that interface or translate between digital circuits and analog circuits are known as mixed-signal circuits.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] Power semiconductor devices are discrete devices or integrated circuits intended for high current or high voltage applications.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] Power integrated circuits combine IC technology with power semiconductor technology, these are sometimes referred to as "smart" power devices.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] Several companies specialize in manufacturing power semiconductors.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] The part numbers of semiconductor devices are often manufacturer specific.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] Nevertheless, there have been attempts at creating standards for type codes, and a subset of devices follow those.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] For discrete devices, for example, there are three standards: JEDEC JESD370B in the United States, Pro Electron in Europe, and Japanese Industrial Standards (JIS).
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] Semiconductor device fabrication is the process used to manufacture semiconductor devices, typically integrated circuits (ICs) such as microprocessors, microcontrollers, and memories (such as RAM and flash memory).
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] It is a multiple-step photolithographic and physico-chemical process (with steps such as thermal oxidation, thin-film deposition, ion implantation, etching) during which electronic circuits are gradually created on a wafer, typically made of pure single-crystal semiconducting material.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] Silicon is almost always used, but various compound semiconductors are used for specialized applications.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] Steps such as etching and photolithography can be used to manufacture other devices, such as LCD and OLED displays.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] The fabrication process is performed in highly specialized semiconductor fabrication plants, also called foundries or "fabs", with the central part being the "clean room".
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] In more advanced semiconductor devices, such as modern 14/10/7 nm nodes, fabrication can take up to 15 weeks, with 11–13 weeks being the industry average.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] Production in advanced fabrication facilities is completely automated, with automated material handling systems taking care of the transport of wafers from machine to machine.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] A wafer often has several integrated circuits, which are called dies as they are pieces diced from a single wafer.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] Individual dies are separated from a finished wafer in a process called die singulation, also called wafer dicing.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] The dies can then undergo further assembly and packaging.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] Within fabrication plants, the wafers are transported inside special sealed plastic boxes called FOUPs.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] FOUPs in many fabs contain an internal nitrogen atmosphere which helps prevent copper from oxidizing on the wafers.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] Copper is used in modern semiconductors for wiring.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] The insides of the processing equipment and FOUPs is kept cleaner than the surrounding air in the cleanroom.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] This internal atmosphere is known as a mini-environment and helps improve yield, which is the number of working devices on a wafer.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] This mini environment is within an EFEM (equipment front end module) which allows a machine to receive FOUPs, and introduces wafers from the FOUPs into the machine.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] Additionally, many machines also handle wafers in clean nitrogen or vacuum environments to reduce contamination and improve process control.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] Fabrication plants need large amounts of liquid nitrogen to maintain the atmosphere inside production machinery and FOUPs, which are constantly purged with nitrogen.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] There can also be an air curtain or a mesh between the FOUP and the EFEM which helps reduce the amount of humidity that enters the FOUP and improves yield.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] Some of the companies that manufacture machines used in the industrial semiconductor fabrication process include ASML, Applied Materials, Tokyo Electron, and Lam Research.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] Semiconductors had been used in the electronics field for some time before the invention of the transistor.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] Around the turn of the 20th century they were quite common as detectors in radios, used in a device called a "cat's whisker" developed by Jagadish Chandra Bose and others.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] These detectors were somewhat troublesome, however, requiring the operator to move a small tungsten filament (the whisker) around the surface of a galena (lead sulfide) or carborundum (silicon carbide) crystal until it suddenly started working.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] Then, over a period of a few hours or days, the cat's whisker would slowly stop working and the process would have to be repeated.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] At the time their operation was completely mysterious.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] After the introduction of the more reliable and amplified vacuum tube based radios, the cat's whisker systems quickly disappeared.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] The "cat's whisker" is a primitive example of a special type of diode still popular today, called a Schottky diode.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] Another early type of semiconductor device is the metal rectifier in which the semiconductor is copper oxide or selenium.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] Westinghouse Electric (1886) was a major manufacturer of these rectifiers.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] During World War II, radar research quickly pushed radar receivers to operate at ever higher frequencies about 4000 MHz and the traditional tube-based radio receivers no longer worked well.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] The introduction of the cavity magnetron from Britain to the United States in 1940 during the Tizard Mission resulted in a pressing need for a practical high-frequency amplifier.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] On a whim, Russell Ohl of Bell Laboratories decided to try a cat's whisker.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] By this point, they had not been in use for a number of years, and no one at the labs had one.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] After hunting one down at a used radio store in Manhattan, he found that it worked much better than tube-based systems.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] Ohl investigated why the cat's whisker functioned so well.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] He spent most of 1939 trying to grow more pure versions of the crystals.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] He soon found that with higher-quality crystals their finicky behavior went away, but so did their ability to operate as a radio detector.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] One day he found one of his purest crystals nevertheless worked well, and it had a clearly visible crack near the middle.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] However, as he moved about the room trying to test it, the detector would mysteriously work, and then stop again.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] After some study he found that the behavior was controlled by the light in the room – more light caused more conductance in the crystal.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] He invited several other people to see this crystal, and Walter Brattain immediately realized there was some sort of junction at the crack.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] Further research cleared up the remaining mystery.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] The crystal had cracked because either side contained very slightly different amounts of the impurities Ohl could not remove – about 0.2%.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] One side of the crystal had impurities that added extra electrons (the carriers of electric current) and made it a "conductor".
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] The other had impurities that wanted to bind to these electrons, making it (what he called) an "insulator".
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] However, when the voltage was reversed the electrons being pushed into the collector would quickly fill up the "holes" (the electron-needy impurities), and conduction would stop almost instantly.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] This junction of the two crystals (or parts of one crystal) created a solid-state diode, and the concept soon became known as semiconduction.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] The mechanism of action when the diode off has to do with the separation of charge carriers around the junction.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] Armed with the knowledge of how these new diodes worked, a vigorous effort began to learn how to build them on demand.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] Teams at Purdue University, Bell Labs, MIT, and the University of Chicago all joined forces to build better crystals.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] Within a year germanium production had been perfected to the point where military-grade diodes were being used in most radar sets.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] After the war, William Shockley decided to attempt the building of a triode-like semiconductor device.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] He secured funding and lab space, and went to work on the problem with Brattain and John Bardeen.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] The key to the development of the transistor was the further understanding of the process of the electron mobility in a semiconductor.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] It was realized that if there were some way to control the flow of the electrons from the emitter to the collector of this newly discovered diode, an amplifier could be built.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] For instance, if contacts are placed on both sides of a single type of crystal, current will not flow between them through the crystal.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] However, if a third contact could then "inject" electrons or holes into the material, the current would flow.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] Actually doing this appeared to be very difficult.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] If the crystal were of any reasonable size, the number of electrons (or holes) required to be injected would have to be very large, making it less than useful as an amplifier because it would require a large injection current to start with.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] That said, the whole idea of the crystal diode was that the crystal itself could provide the electrons over a very small distance, the depletion region.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] The key appeared to be to place the input and output contacts very close together on the surface of the crystal on either side of this region.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] Brattain started working on building such a device, and tantalizing hints of amplification continued to appear as the team worked on the problem.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] Sometimes the system would work but then stop working unexpectedly.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] In one instance a non-working system started working when placed in water.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] Ohl and Brattain eventually developed a new branch of quantum mechanics, which became known as surface physics, to account for the behavior.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] The electrons in any one piece of the crystal would migrate about due to nearby charges.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] Electrons in the emitters, or the "holes" in the collectors, would cluster at the surface of the crystal where they could find their opposite charge "floating around" in the air (or water).
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] Yet they could be pushed away from the surface with the application of a small amount of charge from any other location on the crystal.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] Instead of needing a large supply of injected electrons, a very small number in the right place on the crystal would accomplish the same thing.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] Their understanding solved the problem of needing a very small control area to some degree.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] Instead of needing two separate semiconductors connected by a common, but tiny, region, a single larger surface would serve.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] The electron-emitting and collecting leads would both be placed very close together on the top, with the control lead placed on the base of the crystal.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] When current flowed through this "base" lead, the electrons or holes would be pushed out, across the block of the semiconductor, and collect on the far surface.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] As long as the emitter and collector were very close together, this should allow enough electrons or holes between them to allow conduction to start.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] The Bell team made many attempts to build such a system with various tools but generally failed.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] Setups, where the contacts were close enough, were invariably as fragile as the original cat's whisker detectors had been, and would work briefly, if at all.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] Eventually, they had a practical breakthrough.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] A piece of gold foil was glued to the edge of a plastic wedge, and then the foil was sliced with a razor at the tip of the triangle.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] The result was two very closely spaced contacts of gold.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] When the wedge was pushed down onto the surface of a crystal and voltage was applied to the other side (on the base of the crystal), current started to flow from one contact to the other as the base voltage pushed the electrons away from the base towards the other side near the contacts.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] The point-contact transistor had been invented.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] While the device was constructed a week earlier, Brattain's notes describe the first demonstration to higher-ups at Bell Labs on the afternoon of 23 December 1947, often given as the birthdate of the transistor.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] What is now known as the "p–n–p point-contact germanium transistor" operated as a speech amplifier with a power gain of 18 in that trial.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] John Bardeen, Walter Houser Brattain, and William Bradford Shockley were awarded the 1956 Nobel Prize in physics for their work.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] Bell Telephone Laboratories needed a generic name for their new invention: "Semiconductor Triode", "Solid Triode", "Surface States Triode" [*sic*], "Crystal Triode" and "Iotatron" were all considered, but "transistor", coined by John R.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] Shockley was upset about the device being credited to Brattain and Bardeen, who he felt had built it "behind his back" to take the glory.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] Matters became worse when Bell Labs lawyers found that some of Shockley's own writings on the transistor were close enough to those of an earlier 1925 patent by Julius Edgar Lilienfeld that they thought it best that his name be left off the patent application.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] Shockley was incensed, and decided to demonstrate who was the real brains of the operation.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] A few months later he invented an entirely new, considerably more robust, bipolar junction transistor type of transistor with a layer or 'sandwich' structure, used for the vast majority of all transistors into the 1960s.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] With the fragility problems solved, the remaining problem was purity.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] Making germanium of the required purity was proving to be a serious problem and limited the yield of transistors that actually worked from a given batch of material.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] Germanium's sensitivity to temperature also limited its usefulness.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] Scientists theorized that silicon would be easier to fabricate, but few investigated this possibility.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] Teal was the first to develop a working silicon transistor at the nascent Texas Instruments, giving it a technological edge.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] From the late 1950s, most transistors were silicon-based.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] Within a few years transistor-based products, most notably easily portable radios, were appearing on the market.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] "Zone melting", a technique using a band of molten material moving through the crystal, further increased crystal purity.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] In 1955, Carl Frosch and Lincoln Derick accidentally grew a layer of silicon dioxide over the silicon wafer, for which they observed surface passivation effects.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] By 1957 Frosch and Derick, using masking and predeposition, were able to manufacture silicon dioxide field effect transistors; the first planar transistors, in which drain and source were adjacent at the same surface.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] They showed that silicon dioxide insulated, protected silicon wafers and prevented dopants from diffusing into the wafer.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] At Bell Labs, the importance of Frosch and Derick technique and transistors was immediately realized.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] Results of their work circulated around Bell Labs in the form of BTL memos before being published in 1957.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] At Shockley Semiconductor, Shockley had circulated the preprint of their article in December 1956 to all his senior staff, including Jean Hoerni, who would later invent the planar process in 1959 while at Fairchild Semiconductor.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] Spitzer studied the mechanism of thermally grown oxides, fabricated a high quality Si/SiO2 stack and published their results in 1960.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] Following this research, Mohamed Atalla and Dawon Kahng proposed a silicon MOS transistor in 1959 and successfully demonstrated a working MOS device with their Bell Labs team in 1960.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] Ligenza who developed the diffusion processes, and H.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] With its scalability, and much lower power consumption and higher density than bipolar junction transistors, the MOSFET became the most common type of transistor in computers, electronics, and communications technology such as smartphones.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] The US Patent and Trademark Office calls the MOSFET a "groundbreaking invention that transformed life and culture around the world".
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] Bardeen's 1948 inversion layer concept, forms the basis of CMOS technology today.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] CMOS (complementary MOS) was invented by Chih-Tang Sah and Frank Wanlass at Fairchild Semiconductor in 1963.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] The first report of a floating-gate MOSFET was made by Dawon Kahng and Simon Sze in 1967.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] FinFET (fin field-effect transistor), a type of 3D multi-gate MOSFET, was proposed by H.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor-device] Steinberg in 1967 and first built by Digh Hisamoto and his team of researchers at Hitachi Central Research Laboratory in 1989.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] A **semiconductor** is a material with electrical conductivity between that of a conductor and an insulator.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] Its conductivity can be modified by adding impurities ("doping") to its crystal structure.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] When two regions with different doping levels are present in the same crystal, they form a semiconductor junction.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] The term "semiconductors" is sometimes used to refer to semiconductor devices such as microchips and computer processors, which work using the physical properties of semiconductors.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] The behavior of charge carriers, which include electrons, ions, and electron holes, at these junctions is the basis of diodes, transistors, and most modern electronics.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] Some examples of semiconductors are silicon, germanium, gallium arsenide, and elements near the so-called "metalloid staircase" on the periodic table.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] After silicon, gallium arsenide is the second-most common semiconductor and is used in laser diodes, solar cells, microwave-frequency integrated circuits, and others.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] Silicon is a critical element for fabricating most electronic circuits.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] Semiconductor devices can display a range of different useful properties, such as passing current more easily in one direction than the other, showing variable resistance, and having sensitivity to light or heat.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] Because the electrical properties of a semiconductor material can be modified by doping and by the application of electrical fields or light, devices made from semiconductors can be used for amplification, switching, and energy conversion.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] The term semiconductor is also used to describe materials used in high capacity, medium- to high-voltage cables as part of their insulation, and these materials are often plastic XLPE (cross-linked polyethylene) with carbon black.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] The conductivity of silicon can be increased by adding a small amount (of the order of 1 in 108) of pentavalent (antimony, phosphorus, or arsenic) or trivalent (boron, gallium, indium) atoms.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] This process is known as doping, and the resulting semiconductors are known as doped or extrinsic semiconductors.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] Apart from doping, the conductivity of a semiconductor can be improved by increasing its temperature.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] This is contrary to the behavior of a metal, in which conductivity decreases with an increase in temperature.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] The modern understanding of the properties of a semiconductor relies on quantum physics to explain the movement of charge carriers in a crystal lattice.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] Doping greatly increases the number of charge carriers within the crystal.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] When a semiconductor is doped by Group V elements, they will behave like donors creating free electrons, known as "n-type" doping.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] When a semiconductor is doped by Group III elements, they will behave like acceptors creating free holes, known as "p-type" doping.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] The semiconductor materials used in electronic devices are doped under precise conditions to control the concentration and regions of p- and n-type dopants.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] A single semiconductor device crystal can have many p- and n-type regions; the p–n junctions between these regions are responsible for the useful electronic behavior.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] Using a hot-point probe, one can determine quickly whether a semiconductor sample is p- or n-type.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] A few of the properties of semiconductor materials were observed throughout the mid-19th and first decades of the 20th century.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] The first practical application of semiconductors in electronics was the 1904 development of the cat's-whisker detector, a primitive semiconductor diode used in early radio receivers.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] Developments in quantum physics led in turn to the invention of the transistor in 1947 and the integrated circuit in 1958.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] Semiconductors in their natural state are poor conductors because a current requires flow of electrons, and semiconductors have their valence bands filled, preventing the entire flow of new electrons.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] Several developed techniques allow semiconducting materials to behave like conducting materials, such as doping or gating.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] These modifications have two outcomes: **n-type** and **p-type**.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] These refer to the excess or shortage of electrons, respectively.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] A balanced number of electrons would cause a current to flow throughout the material.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] A difference in the electric potential on a semiconducting material would cause it to leave thermal equilibrium and create a non-equilibrium situation.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] This introduces electrons and holes to the system, which interact via a process called ambipolar diffusion.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] Whenever thermal equilibrium is disturbed in a semiconducting material, the number of holes and electrons changes.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] Such disruptions can occur as a result of a temperature difference or photons, which can enter the system and create electrons and holes.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] The processes that create or annihilate electrons and holes are called generation and recombination, respectively.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] In certain semiconductors, excited electrons can relax by emitting light instead of producing heat.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] Controlling the semiconductor composition and electrical current allows for the manipulation of the emitted light's properties.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] These semiconductors are used in the construction of light-emitting diodes and fluorescent quantum dots.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] Semiconductors with high thermal conductivity can be used for heat dissipation and improving thermal management of electronics.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] They play a crucial role in electric vehicles, high-brightness LEDs and power modules, among other applications.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] Semiconductors have large thermoelectric power factors making them useful in thermoelectric generators, as well as high thermoelectric figures of merit making them useful in thermoelectric coolers.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] The most common semiconducting materials are crystalline solids, but amorphous and liquid semiconductors are also known.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] These include hydrogenated amorphous silicon and mixtures of arsenic, selenium, and tellurium in a variety of proportions.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] These compounds share with better-known semiconductors the properties of intermediate conductivity and a rapid variation of conductivity with temperature, as well as occasional negative resistance.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] Such disordered materials lack the rigid crystalline structure of conventional semiconductors such as silicon.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] They are generally used in thin film structures, which do not require material of higher electronic quality, being relatively insensitive to impurities and radiation damage.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] Almost all of today's electronic technology involves the use of semiconductors, with the most important aspect being integrated circuits (ICs), which are found in desktop computers, laptops, smartphones, and other electronic devices.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] Semiconductors for ICs are mass-produced.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] To create an ideal semiconducting material, chemical purity is paramount.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] Any small imperfection can have a drastic effect on how the semiconducting material behaves due to the scale at which the materials are used.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] A high degree of crystalline perfection is also required, since faults in the crystal structure (such as dislocations, twins, and stacking faults) interfere with the semiconducting properties of the material.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] Crystalline faults are a major cause of defective semiconductor devices.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] The larger the crystal, the more difficult it is to achieve the necessary perfection.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] Current mass production processes use crystal ingots between 100 and 300 mm (3.9 and 11.8 in) in diameter, grown as cylinders and sliced into wafers.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] The round shape characteristic of these wafers comes from single-crystal ingots usually produced using the Czochralski method.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] Silicon wafers were first introduced in the 1940s.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] There is a combination of processes that are used to prepare semiconducting materials for ICs.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] One process is called thermal oxidation, which forms silicon dioxide on the surface of the silicon.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] This is used as a gate insulator and field oxide.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] Other processes are called photomasks and photolithography.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] This process is what creates the patterns on the circuit in the integrated circuit.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] Ultraviolet light is used along with a photoresist layer to create a chemical change that generates the patterns for the circuit.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] The etching is the next process that is required.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] The part of the silicon that was not covered by the photoresist layer from the previous step can now be etched.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] The main process typically used today is called plasma etching.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] Plasma etching usually involves an etch gas pumped in a low-pressure chamber to create plasma.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] A common etch gas is chlorofluorocarbon, or more commonly known Freon.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] A high radio-frequency voltage between the cathode and anode is what creates the plasma in the chamber.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] The silicon wafer is located on the cathode, which causes it to be hit by the positively charged ions that are released from the plasma.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] The result is silicon that is etched anisotropically.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] This is the process that gives the semiconducting material its desired semiconducting properties.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] The process introduces an impure atom to the system, which creates the p–n junction.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] To get the impure atoms embedded in the silicon wafer, the wafer is first put in a 1,100 degree Celsius chamber.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] The atoms are injected in and eventually diffuse with the silicon.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] After the process is completed and the silicon has reached room temperature, the doping process is done and the semiconducting wafer is almost prepared.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] Semiconductors are defined by their unique electric conductive behavior, somewhere between that of a conductor and an insulator.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] The differences between these materials can be understood in terms of the quantum states for electrons, each of which may contain zero or one electron (by the Pauli exclusion principle).
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] These states are associated with the electronic band structure of the material.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] Electrical conductivity arises due to the presence of electrons in states that are delocalized (extending through the material), however in order to transport electrons a state must be *partially filled*, containing an electron only part of the time.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] If the state is always occupied with an electron, then it is inert, blocking the passage of other electrons via that state.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] The energies of these quantum states are critical since a state is partially filled only if its energy is near the Fermi level (see Fermi–Dirac statistics).
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] High conductivity in a material comes from it having many partially filled states and much state delocalization.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] Metals are good electrical conductors and have many partially filled states with energies near their Fermi level.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] Insulators, by contrast, have few partially filled states, their Fermi levels sit within band gaps with few energy states to occupy.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] An (intrinsic) semiconductor has a band gap that is smaller than that of an insulator and at room temperature, significant numbers of electrons can be excited to cross the band gap.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] A pure semiconductor, however, is not very useful, as it is neither a very good insulator nor a very good conductor.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] However, one important feature of semiconductors (and some insulators, known as *semi-insulators*) is that their conductivity can be increased and controlled by doping with impurities and gating with electric fields.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] Doping and gating move either the conduction or valence band much closer to the Fermi level and greatly increase the number of partially filled states.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] Some wider-bandgap semiconductor materials are sometimes referred to as **semi-insulators**.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] When undoped, these have electrical conductivity nearer to that of electrical insulators, however they can be doped (making them as useful as semiconductors).
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] Semi-insulators find niche applications in micro-electronics, such as substrates for HEMT.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] An example of a common semi-insulator is gallium arsenide.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] Some materials, such as titanium dioxide, can even be used as insulating materials for some applications, while being treated as wide-gap semiconductors for other applications.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] The partial filling of the states at the bottom of the conduction band can be understood as adding electrons to that band.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] The electrons do not stay indefinitely (due to the natural thermal recombination) but they can move around for some time.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] The actual concentration of electrons is typically very dilute, and so (unlike in metals) it is possible to think of the electrons in the conduction band of a semiconductor as a sort of classical ideal gas, where the electrons fly around freely without being subject to the Pauli exclusion principle.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] In most semiconductors, the conduction bands have a parabolic dispersion relation, and so these electrons respond to forces (electric field, magnetic field, etc.) much as they would in a vacuum, though with a different effective mass.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] Because the electrons behave like an ideal gas, one may also think about conduction in very simplistic terms such as the Drude model, and introduce concepts such as electron mobility.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] For partial filling at the top of the valence band, it is helpful to introduce the concept of an electron hole.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] Although the electrons in the valence band are always moving around, a completely full valence band is inert, not conducting any current.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] If an electron is taken out of the valence band, then the trajectory that the electron would normally have taken is now missing its charge.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] For the purposes of electric current, this combination of the full valence band, minus the electron, can be converted into a picture of a completely empty band containing a positively charged particle that moves in the same way as the electron.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] This particle is called a hole, and the collection of holes in the valence band can again be understood in simple classical terms (as with the electrons in the conduction band).
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] When ionizing radiation strikes a semiconductor, it may excite an electron out of its energy level and consequently leave a hole.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] This process is known as *electron-hole pair generation*.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] Electron-hole pairs are constantly generated from thermal energy as well, in the absence of any external energy source.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] Electron-hole pairs are also apt to recombine.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] Conservation of energy demands that these recombination events, in which an electron loses an amount of energy larger than the band gap, be accompanied by the emission of thermal energy (in the form of phonons) or radiation (in the form of photons).
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] In some states, the generation and recombination of electron–hole pairs are in equipoise.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] The number of electron-hole pairs in the steady state at a given temperature is determined by quantum statistical mechanics.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] The precise quantum mechanical mechanisms of generation and recombination are governed by the conservation of energy and conservation of momentum.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] The product is a function of the temperature, as the probability of getting enough thermal energy to produce a pair increases with temperature, being approximately exp(−*E*G/*kT*), where *k* is the Boltzmann constant, *T* is the absolute temperature and *E*G is bandgap.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] The probability of meeting is increased by carrier traps – impurities or dislocations which can trap an electron or hole and hold it until a pair is completed.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] Such carrier traps are sometimes purposely added to reduce the time needed to reach the steady-state.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] The conductivity of semiconductors may easily be modified by introducing impurities into their crystal lattice.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] The process of adding controlled impurities to a semiconductor is known as **doping**.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] The amount of impurity, or dopant, added to an *intrinsic* (pure) semiconductor varies its level of conductivity.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] Doped semiconductors are referred to as *extrinsic*.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] By adding impurity to the pure semiconductors, the electrical conductivity may be varied by factors of thousands or millions.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] A 1 cm3 specimen of a metal or semiconductor has the order of 1022 atoms.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] In a metal, every atom donates at least one free electron for conduction, thus 1 cm3 of metal contains on the order of 1022 free electrons, whereas a 1 cm3 sample of pure germanium at 20 °C contains about 4.2×1022 atoms, but only 2.5×1013 free electrons and 2.5×1013 holes.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] The addition of 0.001% of arsenic (an impurity) donates an extra 1017 free electrons in the same volume and the electrical conductivity is increased by a factor of 10,000.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] The materials chosen as suitable dopants depend on the atomic properties of both the dopant and the material to be doped.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] In general, dopants that produce the desired controlled changes are classified as either electron acceptors or donors.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] Semiconductors doped with *donor* impurities are called *n-type*, while those doped with *acceptor* impurities are known as *p-type*.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] The n and p type designations indicate which charge carrier acts as the material's majority carrier.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] The opposite carrier is called the minority carrier, which exists due to thermal excitation at a much lower concentration compared to the majority carrier.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] For example, the pure semiconductor silicon has four valence electrons that bond each silicon atom to its neighbors.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] In silicon, the most common dopants are group III and group V elements.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] Group III elements all contain three valence electrons, causing them to function as acceptors when used to dope silicon.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] When an acceptor atom replaces a silicon atom in the crystal, a vacant state (an electron "hole") is created, which can move around the lattice and function as a charge carrier.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] Group V elements have five valence electrons, which allows them to act as a donor; substitution of these atoms for silicon creates an extra free electron.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] Therefore, a silicon crystal doped with boron creates a p-type semiconductor whereas one doped with phosphorus results in an n-type material.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] During manufacture, dopants can be diffused into the semiconductor body by contact with gaseous compounds of the desired element, or ion implantation can be used to accurately position the doped regions.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] Some materials, when rapidly cooled to a glassy amorphous state, have semiconducting properties.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] These include B, Si, Ge, Se, and Te, and there are multiple theories to explain them.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] The history of the understanding of semiconductors begins with experiments on the electrical properties of materials.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] The properties of the time-temperature coefficient of resistance, rectification, and light-sensitivity were observed starting in the early 19th century.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] Thomas Johann Seebeck was the first to notice that semiconductors exhibit special feature such that experiment concerning an Seebeck effect emerged with much stronger result when applying semiconductors, in 1821.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] In 1833, Michael Faraday reported that the resistance of specimens of silver sulfide decreases when they are heated.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] This is contrary to the behavior of metallic substances such as copper.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] In 1839, Alexandre Edmond Becquerel reported observation of a voltage between a solid and a liquid electrolyte, when struck by light, the photovoltaic effect.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] In 1873, Willoughby Smith observed that selenium resistors exhibit decreasing resistance when light falls on them.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] In 1874, Karl Ferdinand Braun observed conduction and rectification in metallic sulfides, although this effect had been discovered earlier by Peter Munck af Rosenschöld (sv) writing for the *Annalen der Physik und Chemie* in 1835; Rosenschöld's findings were ignored.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] Simon Sze stated that Braun's research was the earliest systematic study of semiconductor devices.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] Also in 1874, Arthur Schuster found that a copper oxide layer on wires had rectification properties that ceased when the wires are cleaned.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] William Grylls Adams and Richard Evans Day observed the photovoltaic effect in selenium in 1876.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] A unified explanation of these phenomena required a theory of solid-state physics, which developed greatly in the first half of the 20th century.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] In 1878 Edwin Herbert Hall demonstrated the deflection of flowing charge carriers by an applied magnetic field, the Hall effect.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] Thomson in 1897 prompted theories of electron-based conduction in solids.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] Karl Baedeker, by observing a Hall effect with the reverse sign to that in metals, theorized that copper iodide had positive charge carriers.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] Johan Koenigsberger classified solid materials like metals, insulators, and "variable conductors" in 1914 although his student Josef Weiss already introduced the term ***Halbleiter*** (a semiconductor in modern meaning) in his Ph.D. thesis in 1910.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] Felix Bloch published a theory of the movement of electrons through atomic lattices in 1928.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] In 1930, Bernhard Gudden stated that conductivity in semiconductors was due to minor concentrations of impurities.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] By 1931, the band theory of conduction had been established by Alan Herries Wilson and the concept of band gaps had been developed.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] Schottky and Nevill Francis Mott developed models of the potential barrier and of the characteristics of a metal–semiconductor junction.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] By 1938, Boris Davydov had developed a theory of the copper-oxide rectifier, identifying the effect of the p–n junction and the importance of minority carriers and surface states.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] Agreement between theoretical predictions (based on developing quantum mechanics) and experimental results was sometimes poor.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] This was later explained by John Bardeen as due to the extreme "structure sensitive" behavior of semiconductors, whose properties change dramatically based on tiny amounts of impurities.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] Commercially pure materials of the 1920s containing varying proportions of trace contaminants produced differing experimental results.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] This spurred the development of improved material refining techniques, culminating in modern semiconductor refineries producing materials with parts-per-trillion purity.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] Devices using semiconductors were at first constructed based on empirical knowledge before semiconductor theory provided a guide to the construction of more capable and reliable devices.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] Alexander Graham Bell used the light-sensitive property of selenium to transmit sound over a beam of light in 1880.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] A working solar cell, of low efficiency, was constructed by Charles Fritts in 1883, using a metal plate coated with selenium and a thin layer of gold; the device became commercially useful in photographic light meters in the 1930s.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] Point-contact microwave detector rectifiers made of lead sulfide were used by Jagadish Chandra Bose in 1904; the cat's-whisker detector using natural galena or other materials became a common device in the development of radio.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] However, it was somewhat unpredictable in operation and required manual adjustment for best performance.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] Round observed light emission when electric current passed through silicon carbide crystals, the principle behind the light-emitting diode.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] Oleg Losev observed similar light emission in 1922, but at the time the effect had no practical use.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] Power rectifiers, using copper oxide and selenium, were developed in the 1920s and became commercially important as an alternative to vacuum tube rectifiers.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] The first semiconductor devices used galena, including German physicist Ferdinand Braun's crystal detector in 1874 and Indian physicist Jagadish Chandra Bose's radio crystal detector in 1901.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] In the years preceding World War II, infrared detection and communications devices prompted research into lead-sulfide and lead-selenide materials.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] These devices were used for detecting ships and aircraft, for infrared rangefinders, and for voice communication systems.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] The point-contact crystal detector became vital for microwave radio systems since available vacuum tube devices could not serve as detectors above about 4000 MHz; advanced radar systems relied on the fast response of crystal detectors.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] Considerable research and development of silicon materials occurred during the war to develop detectors of consistent quality.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] Detector and power rectifiers could not amplify a signal.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] Many efforts were made to develop a solid-state amplifier and were successful in developing a device called the point contact transistor which could amplify 20 dB or more.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] In 1922, Oleg Losev developed two-terminal, negative resistance amplifiers for radio, but he died in the Siege of Leningrad after successful completion.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] In 1926, Julius Edgar Lilienfeld patented a device resembling a field-effect transistor, but it was not practical.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] Holden started investigating solid-state amplifiers in 1938.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] The first p–n junction in silicon was observed by Russell Ohl about 1941 when a specimen was found to be light-sensitive, with a sharp boundary between p-type impurity at one end and n-type at the other.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] A slice cut from the specimen at the p–n boundary developed a voltage when exposed to light.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] The first working transistor was a point-contact transistor invented by John Bardeen, Walter Houser Brattain, and William Shockley at Bell Labs in 1947.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] Shockley had earlier theorized a field-effect amplifier made from germanium and silicon, but he failed to build such a working device, before eventually using germanium to invent the point-contact transistor.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] In France, during the war, Herbert Mataré had observed amplification between adjacent point contacts on a germanium base.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] After the war, Mataré's group announced their "Transistron" amplifier only shortly after Bell Labs announced the "transistor".
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] In 1954, physical chemist Morris Tanenbaum fabricated the first silicon junction transistor at Bell Labs.
[src:semiconductor-physics/semiconductor] However, early junction transistors were relatively bulky devices that were difficult to manufacture on a mass-production basis, which limited them to a number of specialised applications.
